{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd2a662b-151c-44b8-8ecd-e58fb36640d4","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`, etc.).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject the interface** into classes that need file I/O.\n4. **Mock it in tests** using your preferred mocking framework.\n\nAlternatively, use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides exactly this out of the box (`IFileSystem`, `IFile`, `IDirectory`) along with an in-memory test file system (`MockFileSystem`), saving you from writing the wrapper yourself.\n\n```csharp\n// Registration\nservices.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();\n\n// Usage\npublic class MyService(IFileSystem fs)\n{\n    public string Load(string path) => fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n\n// Test\nvar mockFs = new MockFileSystem();\nmockFs.AddFile(\"/data.txt\", new MockFileData(\"hello\"));\nvar svc = new MyService(mockFs);\nAssert.Equal(\"hello\", svc.Load(\"/data.txt\"));\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe00a3e5-8036-4754-a97f-831f845e4abc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":361,"requestId":"E3E7:FA207:21EAE87:25912E7:6A0535C3"},"id":"89ad29c8-967a-432a-94eb-7dc6c438954b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T02:39:09.426Z","parentId":"70ed29e9-f1de-4059-9a61-d86d0ccaf2ae"}
